nial-era cultural collaboration between the colonizers and the colonized, and their denial in divided national narrations during the postcolonial aftermath, offers insights into the paradoxical nature of colonial collaboration, which Kwon characterizes as embodying desire and intimacy with violence and coercion. Through the case study of the formation and repression of imperial subjects between Korea and Japan, Kwon considers the imbrications of colonialism and modernity and the entwined legacies of colonial and Cold War histories in the Asia-Pacific more broadly.   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 25. Nov 2020) 0aImperialism in literature. 0aJapanese literature - Korean authors - History and criticism. 0aJapanese literaturexKorean authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aLanguage and languages in literature. 0aModernism (Literature)zJapan. 0aModernism (Literature)zKorea. 0aPostcolonialism in literature. 7aHISTORY / Asia / Korea.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311071182040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822375401zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822375401423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822375401.jpg  a978-3-11-071182-0  DUK eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles